WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.590 --> 00:00:04.640
Prof: We're coming to
the end of the course,

00:00:04.640 --> 00:00:08.956
and the last couple of
lectures, the last few are

00:00:08.956 --> 00:00:13.812
social issues and then we'll
have a very short time for

00:00:13.812 --> 00:00:16.600
environment, unfortunately.
 

00:00:16.600 --> 00:00:18.720
Today we're going to talk about
abortion.

00:00:18.720 --> 00:00:24.075
It's kind of a unique topic in
the sense that in the United

00:00:24.075 --> 00:00:27.090
States it's--
if you have a global

00:00:27.090 --> 00:00:31.494
perspective, in most of the
world abortion is not a big

00:00:31.494 --> 00:00:33.370
controversial issue.
 

00:00:33.370 --> 00:00:38.123
In the United States it's just
gone sky high as kind of the

00:00:38.123 --> 00:00:42.140
central issue in the American
debate on values.

00:00:42.140 --> 00:00:44.140
It has tremendous political
significance.

00:00:44.140 --> 00:00:48.805
Large numbers of people vote
for a candidate for,

00:00:48.805 --> 00:00:52.887
say president,
based solely on whether they

00:00:52.887 --> 00:00:55.900
are pro-choice or pro-life.
 

00:00:55.900 --> 00:00:59.519
One of the things you've got to
figure out, or try to,

00:00:59.519 --> 00:01:02.728
is why has this become so
important an issue.

00:01:02.728 --> 00:01:06.290
I think one of the reasons is
that it encapsulates

00:01:06.290 --> 00:01:10.650
diametrically opposed views of
our roles in everyday life.

00:01:10.650 --> 00:01:16.870
People perceive it as an
everyday kind of issue.

00:01:16.870 --> 00:01:18.360
What are the roles that I'm
talking about?

00:01:18.360 --> 00:01:21.470
Sex roles, work roles,
husband and wife roles,

00:01:21.470 --> 00:01:23.819
motherhood and fatherhood
roles;

00:01:23.819 --> 00:01:28.513
all of those--how you perceive
yourself in those roles will

00:01:28.513 --> 00:01:33.450
very much determine how you feel
about the abortion debate.

00:01:33.450 --> 00:01:37.795
For instance,
both sides in the debate agree

00:01:37.795 --> 00:01:41.129
that the issue is about murder.
 

00:01:41.129 --> 00:01:44.739
A pro-lifer sees images of a
three month old fetus,

00:01:44.739 --> 00:01:48.437
which even though only about
the size of your finger they

00:01:48.437 --> 00:01:50.860
see--
they're having visuals of blown

00:01:50.860 --> 00:01:54.590
up photographs and I'm sure
you've all seen those things and

00:01:54.590 --> 00:01:56.930
it already looks quite baby
like,

00:01:56.930 --> 00:02:01.328
and thinks of it of being
dismembered and murdered.

00:02:01.328 --> 00:02:04.819
A pro-choicer also sees it
about murder,

00:02:04.819 --> 00:02:07.560
but she, in her mind,
sees a young woman,

00:02:07.560 --> 00:02:10.639
maybe herself,
in a back alley abortion,

00:02:10.639 --> 00:02:14.389
being butchered and possibly
murdered.

00:02:14.389 --> 00:02:19.790
Almost everyone of the older
generation of pro-choice women

00:02:19.790 --> 00:02:23.610
has either themselves had an
abortion,

00:02:23.610 --> 00:02:27.370
or has had a friend who has had
an abortion,

00:02:27.370 --> 00:02:29.330
and they perceived it as
lifesaving,

00:02:29.330 --> 00:02:31.449
or if it was a back alley,
unsuccessful one,

00:02:31.449 --> 00:02:37.288
as a life depriving situation.
 

00:02:37.288 --> 00:02:41.340
Both sides agree that the issue
is about babies and motherhood.

00:02:41.340 --> 00:02:45.328
A pro-life mother thinks that
babies are so precious that

00:02:45.328 --> 00:02:48.960
whenever they come they will be
loved and wanted.

00:02:48.960 --> 00:02:52.788
There is no such thing as an
unloved or unwanted baby.

00:02:52.788 --> 00:02:56.973
A pro-choice mother thinks that
babies are so precious that they

00:02:56.973 --> 00:03:00.826
should only be had when the
woman really wants the baby and

00:03:00.826 --> 00:03:04.479
is in the situation in life
where they have resources to

00:03:04.479 --> 00:03:06.340
take care of the baby.
 

00:03:06.340 --> 00:03:09.860
Both sides agree that the issue
is about sex.

00:03:09.860 --> 00:03:14.074
A pro-life woman thinks that
sex is so special that it should

00:03:14.074 --> 00:03:18.288
be guarded by strong religious
and social controls so that it

00:03:18.288 --> 00:03:21.240
always has an almost sacred
character.

00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:25.014
A pro-choice woman thinks sex
is so special that it should be

00:03:25.014 --> 00:03:28.852
freed from worry about pregnancy
and disease so that it can be

00:03:28.852 --> 00:03:31.620
enjoyed as a unique sharing of
intimacy.

00:03:31.620 --> 00:03:35.538
Both sides agree that the issue
is about the status of women.

00:03:35.538 --> 00:03:39.167
Pro-life women think that women
are so important that their

00:03:39.167 --> 00:03:42.419
special life role of motherhood
must be protected.

00:03:42.419 --> 00:03:46.438
Pro-choice women think that
women are so important that they

00:03:46.438 --> 00:03:50.593
should have every bit as much
control over their life roles as

00:03:50.593 --> 00:03:51.479
men have.
 

00:03:51.479 --> 00:03:56.166
Just viewed in that way,
one of the interesting things

00:03:56.166 --> 00:04:01.030
about this abortion debate is
that the two sides on--

00:04:01.030 --> 00:04:03.986
if you really get down to what
the fundamental values of the

00:04:03.986 --> 00:04:06.259
two sides are,
they're not different.

00:04:06.259 --> 00:04:08.038
They apply them differently.
 

00:04:08.038 --> 00:04:12.245
They're thinking of different
instances, of different real

00:04:12.245 --> 00:04:16.230
situations in which to apply
these rather same kinds of

00:04:16.230 --> 00:04:18.370
fundamental human values.
 

00:04:18.370 --> 00:04:21.324
All right, well obviously this
is not a philosophy course and

00:04:21.324 --> 00:04:24.129
not in the slightest set up to
debate the pros and cons of

00:04:24.129 --> 00:04:27.026
abortion,
and that's also a kind of

00:04:27.026 --> 00:04:28.439
sterile debate.
 

00:04:28.439 --> 00:04:32.574
Anybody--has anybody changed
their mind about abortion since

00:04:32.574 --> 00:04:36.290
they were knee high to a
grasshopper, in the class?

00:04:36.290 --> 00:04:38.100
I don't want to know which
direction you went.

00:04:38.100 --> 00:04:41.879
One has changed her mind,
two have changed their mind.

00:04:41.879 --> 00:04:43.790
That's a high ratio.
 

00:04:43.790 --> 00:04:47.307
Does anybody know anybody who's
changed their minds,

00:04:47.307 --> 00:04:51.170
except for yourself of course,
one or two more people;

00:04:51.170 --> 00:04:52.509
three another one.
 

00:04:52.509 --> 00:04:57.793
I mean there's so much about
abortion out there and yet

00:04:57.793 --> 00:05:03.370
people's attitude toward it is
set very early in life,

00:05:03.370 --> 00:05:06.036
by again, these very
fundamental images of what we're

00:05:06.036 --> 00:05:08.600
talking about when we're talking
about abortion.

00:05:08.600 --> 00:05:13.786
No matter how it's argued,
people basically don't change

00:05:13.786 --> 00:05:15.389
their opinions.
 

00:05:15.389 --> 00:05:19.769
I'm not going to debate pros
and cons at all.

00:05:19.769 --> 00:05:23.709
I'm going to give you as many
facts about abortion as I can

00:05:23.709 --> 00:05:26.019
explain to you:
the demography,

00:05:26.019 --> 00:05:27.860
and the biology,
and the statistics,

00:05:27.860 --> 00:05:31.199
and all of that kind of stuff.
 

00:05:31.199 --> 00:05:34.795
There are a number of important
things that you should know

00:05:34.795 --> 00:05:35.850
about abortion.
 

00:05:35.850 --> 00:05:39.389
The first is that induced
abortion is common;

00:05:39.389 --> 00:05:43.230
it's a very frequent situation
in the world.

00:05:43.230 --> 00:05:49.394
There's one abortion for every
3.2 live births,

00:05:49.394 --> 00:05:51.940
so that's 1 in 3.
 

00:05:51.940 --> 00:05:57.095
Each year about 3% of women in
childbearing ages have an

00:05:57.095 --> 00:06:00.541
abortion,
and if you consider a 30 year

00:06:00.541 --> 00:06:05.348
reproductive lifespan with each
woman having a 3% chance each

00:06:05.348 --> 00:06:06.870
year that's 90%.
 

00:06:06.870 --> 00:06:09.524
That means that,
in the world,

00:06:09.524 --> 00:06:14.649
the average woman has a 0.9
chance, very close to one.

00:06:14.649 --> 00:06:20.577
Basically, for every woman in
the world, there's one abortion

00:06:20.577 --> 00:06:23.639
in her reproductive lifetime.
 

00:06:23.639 --> 00:06:28.267
Of course this is an average,
some women have many more,

00:06:28.267 --> 00:06:30.540
and some women have none.
 

00:06:30.540 --> 00:06:34.595
There are three,
actually three or four standard

00:06:34.595 --> 00:06:39.860
ways of measuring and expressing
the frequency of abortion.

00:06:39.860 --> 00:06:43.088
One is simply the number of
abortions in the world,

00:06:43.088 --> 00:06:45.800
or in the country,
or whatever you want.

00:06:45.800 --> 00:06:50.172
The latest estimate,
all of these latest estimates

00:06:50.172 --> 00:06:51.690
come from 2003.
 

00:06:51.690 --> 00:06:56.297
About every five years people
try to tally up abortion

00:06:56.297 --> 00:07:01.774
statistics from around the world
and that's a very difficult job

00:07:01.774 --> 00:07:06.439
because wherever its illegal,
you have very great difficulty

00:07:06.439 --> 00:07:07.579
getting statistics.
 

00:07:07.579 --> 00:07:12.012
In many places--especially
where there's religious

00:07:12.012 --> 00:07:17.077
opposition to abortion they--the
statistics include it as

00:07:17.077 --> 00:07:19.519
'menstrual regulation.'
 

00:07:19.519 --> 00:07:23.490
That means a woman has missed
her menses and,

00:07:23.490 --> 00:07:25.910
of course, everyone knows
that's a good thing,

00:07:25.910 --> 00:07:28.858
so you have to restore the
menses and you do exactly what's

00:07:28.858 --> 00:07:29.569
an abortion.
 

00:07:29.569 --> 00:07:33.029
Everybody in the country will
understand what's going on,

00:07:33.029 --> 00:07:35.750
but the statistic is menstrual
regulation.

00:07:35.750 --> 00:07:38.379
Depending on what's happening
in the country,

00:07:38.379 --> 00:07:41.166
you usually have to add one
part of the government

00:07:41.166 --> 00:07:44.466
statistics about menstrual
regulation to another part which

00:07:44.466 --> 00:07:45.490
says abortion.
 

00:07:45.490 --> 00:07:49.218
Anyway, there are lots of
problems in collecting these

00:07:49.218 --> 00:07:53.230
numbers but they're probably
fairly decent because they're

00:07:53.230 --> 00:07:56.218
very sophisticated--
demographically very

00:07:56.218 --> 00:08:00.115
sophisticated people are the
ones that try to make these best

00:08:00.115 --> 00:08:00.959
estimates.
 

00:08:00.959 --> 00:08:05.543
The number of abortions in the
world is now considered to be 42

00:08:05.543 --> 00:08:09.980
million per year and the number
has stayed in that range,

00:08:09.980 --> 00:08:12.745
the 40 to 50 million range,
for at least the last two

00:08:12.745 --> 00:08:14.863
decades,
when there's fairly good

00:08:14.863 --> 00:08:16.779
collection of the statistics.
 

00:08:16.779 --> 00:08:17.939
So that's the number.
 

00:08:17.939 --> 00:08:22.882
The abortion rate is defined as
the abortions per 1,000 women in

00:08:22.882 --> 00:08:26.964
reproductive ages which is
usually taken as 15 to 44,

00:08:26.964 --> 00:08:28.220
or 15 to 49.
 

00:08:28.220 --> 00:08:31.410
For the world it's 29 per 1,000.
 

00:08:31.410 --> 00:08:34.375
So, every year,
per 1,000 women,

00:08:34.375 --> 00:08:36.480
29 have an abortion.
 

00:08:36.480 --> 00:08:39.058
That's the 3% that I mentioned
earlier;

00:08:39.058 --> 00:08:41.379
if it was 30 it would be
exactly 3%.

00:08:41.379 --> 00:08:45.750
Both the highest rate and the
lowest rates are found in

00:08:45.750 --> 00:08:46.480
Europe.
 

00:08:46.480 --> 00:08:51.690
Western Europe has 12 abortions
per 1,000 women per year;

00:08:51.690 --> 00:08:58.136
Eastern Europe has four times
as many, 44 per 1,000 women per

00:08:58.136 --> 00:08:58.889
year.
 

00:08:58.889 --> 00:09:02.500
It's interesting that of the
whole world,

00:09:02.500 --> 00:09:04.407
within Europe,
which we sometimes consider a

00:09:04.407 --> 00:09:06.951
cultural entity,
it isn't with respect to

00:09:06.951 --> 00:09:11.350
abortion, the highest and lowest
numbers are found in Europe.

00:09:11.350 --> 00:09:15.852
Another way of expressing it is
the abortion ratio which is the

00:09:15.852 --> 00:09:19.921
abortions per 100 live births,
and that's what I told you

00:09:19.921 --> 00:09:20.720
before.
 

00:09:20.720 --> 00:09:22.928
One abortion for every 3.2 live
births.

00:09:22.928 --> 00:09:26.980
In the world,
that comes out to 31 per 100

00:09:26.980 --> 00:09:31.330
and this ranges from 12 in
middle Africa,

00:09:31.330 --> 00:09:35.440
it's a low rate,
to 105 in Eastern Europe,

00:09:35.440 --> 00:09:39.000
again Eastern Europe has the
highest in the world.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:42.008
Note that 105;
we're talking about abortions

00:09:42.008 --> 00:09:42.740
per live births.
 

00:09:42.740 --> 00:09:45.570
When you have 105 abortions per
100 live births,

00:09:45.570 --> 00:09:48.220
there are more abortions than
live births.

00:09:48.220 --> 00:09:53.860
So, at 100 per 100,
half of pregnancies are

00:09:53.860 --> 00:09:57.889
terminated with an abortion.
 

00:09:57.889 --> 00:10:00.895
Interestingly,
the abortion rate is the same,

00:10:00.895 --> 00:10:04.585
is very closely the same,
independent of whether you're

00:10:04.585 --> 00:10:08.070
in a developing country or a
developed country.

00:10:08.070 --> 00:10:11.841
The rate in developed countries
is 26 per 1,000 and in

00:10:11.841 --> 00:10:14.759
developing countries it's 29 per
1,000;

00:10:14.759 --> 00:10:16.990
not a huge difference.
 

00:10:16.990 --> 00:10:21.534
China, which everyone worries
about the forced abortions

00:10:21.534 --> 00:10:26.412
there, has about 20% of the
world's population and has about

00:10:26.412 --> 00:10:29.139
20% of the world's abortions.
 

00:10:29.139 --> 00:10:32.886
Another--the last number that
I'll tell you about that people

00:10:32.886 --> 00:10:34.881
calculate,
is what's called the total

00:10:34.881 --> 00:10:37.201
abortion rate,
which is calculated exactly in

00:10:37.201 --> 00:10:39.428
the same way as the total
fertility rate.

00:10:39.428 --> 00:10:43.350
You take the age specific
abortion rate and add it up,

00:10:43.350 --> 00:10:47.173
and it's the number of
abortions that the average woman

00:10:47.173 --> 00:10:51.210
would have in her lifetime if
she continues with the rates

00:10:51.210 --> 00:10:55.460
that are present at the time you
collect the statistics.

00:10:55.460 --> 00:10:59.115
Again, I mention this,
in the world it's 0.9 very

00:10:59.115 --> 00:11:03.379
close to 1, the average woman
will have 1 abortion in her

00:11:03.379 --> 00:11:04.370
lifetime.
 

00:11:04.370 --> 00:11:08.640
It ranges from a low of 0.2,
one abortion per every five

00:11:08.640 --> 00:11:12.679
women in several countries,
to a high of 1.7 in Cuba,

00:11:12.679 --> 00:11:16.019
almost two abortions per woman
in Cuba.

00:11:16.019 --> 00:11:22.155
Well I'll talk later about a
very interesting situation in

00:11:22.155 --> 00:11:22.908
Cuba.
 

00:11:22.908 --> 00:11:26.744
Over time, as I said,
the number of abortions is

00:11:26.744 --> 00:11:30.414
really, on the big scale,
a couple of decades,

00:11:30.414 --> 00:11:32.700
staying pretty constant.
 

00:11:32.700 --> 00:11:36.860
But, from the last compilation
in 1995, the estimate was 46

00:11:36.860 --> 00:11:41.308
million abortions and now it's
down to 42 million abortions.

00:11:41.308 --> 00:11:44.320
There has been a very small
drop in the number of abortions.

00:11:44.320 --> 00:11:49.783
Where do you think all of that
drop has occurred?

00:11:49.783 --> 00:11:54.025
Eastern Europe;
again they had an extremely

00:11:54.025 --> 00:11:57.510
high abortion rate,
it was the mechanism of

00:11:57.510 --> 00:12:00.797
contraception there,
and they're gradually becoming

00:12:00.797 --> 00:12:04.019
accustomed to contraception so
their abortion rate is going

00:12:04.019 --> 00:12:06.923
down,
three-quarters of the change in

00:12:06.923 --> 00:12:10.490
the whole world is all due to
Eastern Europe.

00:12:10.490 --> 00:12:15.460
The United States looks pretty
much like the rest of the world.

00:12:15.460 --> 00:12:21.042
There's 1 abortion for every
3.2 live births here which is

00:12:21.042 --> 00:12:26.428
exactly the number that is the
average for the world.

00:12:26.428 --> 00:12:30.481
In the United States there are
1.3 million abortions in again

00:12:30.481 --> 00:12:34.129
2003, the last time those
statistics were collected.

00:12:37.970 --> 00:12:43.019
The rate is 21.3 abortions per
1,000 women.

00:12:43.019 --> 00:12:45.758
If you look per woman,
the U.S.

00:12:45.758 --> 00:12:49.500
looks a little better than per
births,

00:12:49.500 --> 00:12:53.879
that the total abortion rate
for the United States is 0.64

00:12:53.879 --> 00:12:56.659
per woman,
that's mean two-thirds of--the

00:12:56.659 --> 00:13:00.101
average is two-thirds of women
will have an abortion during

00:13:00.101 --> 00:13:02.822
their lifetime,
whereas, the world is closer to

00:13:02.822 --> 00:13:03.080
one.
 

00:13:03.080 --> 00:13:06.653
So, we have a somewhat lower
rate, and again,

00:13:06.653 --> 00:13:11.123
the difference is the use of
contraception and I'll talk

00:13:11.123 --> 00:13:12.830
about that later.
 

00:13:12.830 --> 00:13:16.159
The United States,
although somewhat better than

00:13:16.159 --> 00:13:20.269
the world average in this,
is not nearly as good as 0.2;

00:13:20.269 --> 00:13:21.879
remember I said ours is 0.64.
 

00:13:21.879 --> 00:13:26.614
Belgium, Germany and
Switzerland all are down at 0.2,

00:13:26.614 --> 00:13:31.711
so less than a third of the
number of abortions per woman

00:13:31.711 --> 00:13:33.259
that we have.
 

00:13:33.259 --> 00:13:38.666
A cohort of 1,000 women going
through their reproductive life

00:13:38.666 --> 00:13:42.053
will have 639 abortions,
and that's assuming,

00:13:42.053 --> 00:13:44.918
we currently have been having a
reducing rate of abortion,

00:13:44.918 --> 00:13:49.450
here it presumes that that rate
will stay down.

00:13:49.450 --> 00:13:53.801
Expanding out to the world
again, abortion can be a major

00:13:53.801 --> 00:13:58.628
method of fertility control,
especially when a country first

00:13:58.628 --> 00:14:01.668
goes through its fertility
transition.

00:14:01.668 --> 00:14:06.424
One of the fastest fertility
transitions in the world was in

00:14:06.424 --> 00:14:08.278
Japan, of all places.
 

00:14:08.278 --> 00:14:11.351
Where they halved the
birthrate--the birthrate in

00:14:11.351 --> 00:14:14.360
Japan was cut in half between
1947 and 1957,

00:14:14.360 --> 00:14:18.804
in ten years it went down to
half, from 34 per 1,000 women to

00:14:18.804 --> 00:14:21.469
17,
and it's remained at that level

00:14:21.469 --> 00:14:25.548
more or less until 1979 and now
it's getting even lower.

00:14:25.548 --> 00:14:35.288
Here is--this is the
interesting case of Japan.

00:14:35.288 --> 00:14:38.245
This is the years
1949--remember MacArthur,

00:14:38.245 --> 00:14:42.256
the U.S. Administration of
Japan was still sort of tailing

00:14:42.256 --> 00:14:46.548
down at that time and we're
looking at a ten year span.

00:14:46.548 --> 00:14:49.496
This is the number of
pregnancies, which is births

00:14:49.496 --> 00:14:52.065
plus abortions,
and you'll notice that during

00:14:52.065 --> 00:14:54.288
this time,
during this ten year time,

00:14:54.288 --> 00:14:57.755
the number of pregnancies
really does not change an awful

00:14:57.755 --> 00:15:00.409
lot;
notice 2,700 to

00:15:00.409 --> 00:15:05.000
2,900,2,600,2,800,2,800,2,600.
 

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:08.490
So the number of pregnancies
does not change.

